 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucrazywizzy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Crazy Wizzy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 127<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/20/01 6:55:39 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: abusive beggers...</span><hr size=1> I have been playing this game for a year and a half and have never asked for more than a SoW for a CR or the run across the spiders in FV <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  or the occasional clarity when I was desperate for mana, and these days, the wis/int buff when working on my tailoring <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  When I first started playing, I met someone in BB, Teer a cleric.  He (in RL) befriended me and would often show up with a ring with 2 int or some other small thing in thanks for helping him with things.  I thought I was the shit even though I later learned that those items were small and cost genearlly not a lot.  It was nice to get but I never asked him for anything.<br>
<br>
Since then, I have tried to repay that kindness to other true newbies when I see them, which is not often.  When I am in NFP working on my tailoring I will look for new monks and give them the wu's I am making instead of selling it to a vendor.  Or, if I get something off a mob that I think someone could use, instead of dropping it, I will often shout to the zone to come and get it someone.<br>
<br>
Recently though, I have had some very bad expierences with this.  I was in NRO and some shield dropped off a mob.  It was a decent shield for a young player, so I shouted to the zone to come get it.  Well a guy showed up for it and I gave it to him, then notieced that he was duel weapon equipped and had better armour than he should have for his level.  He did not equip the shield, did not say thanks, just ran off.  Then, while in NFP a day latter, a young level 1 cleric came begging me for items or pp.  She was very polite and nice and was begging nicely.  I should have had a clue from the fact that she was a level 1 High Elf in NFP (I dont think I went that far from Felwithe till I was at least level 10).  SInce she was not being rude, I said I would give her something that she could sell to buy her spells or something, but that I had nothing a cleric could really use.  SO since I was again practicing my tailoring skills, I gave her a Wu's shirt.  Two seconds later she is shouting to the zone PC on Wu's fighting shirt please.  THen I knew.  ahh well.<br>
<br>
But the best one lately was a couple of weeks ago, again in NFP where a young bard was begging everyone there for pp and items.  The entire zone got so tired of it that they were telling her off.  She never got it, and kept right on harassing folks.  SOmeone told her that in the time she was wasteing begging, she could have gotten some exp and some plat by killing something (oh my, what a novel idea), and she still did not get it.  Finally my guild mate, a level 53 bard, went up to her and started chatting.  She was of course begging him also, and he led her on and messed with her a bit.  When he inspected her, he found she was twinked!  GO figure that one. THen when he royaly told her off, and sort of bugged her a bit to show her what it feels like to be harassed, she threatedned to report him to the GM!<br>
<br>
And what is with this thought that every person who wears a dress can cast clarity?  I have gotten so many requests for that lately.  I will port in to a zone, at the wizard spires, right in front of someone (should be the first clue) and they will say Hail, then they will say can I plz have a clarity?  Do they even bother to do a /who first?  I told one guy the other day, sorry, no I cant cast that, and he said then how bout a breeze? !!!!!!!  Just because you wear a dress does not mean you can cast clarity.  My bard guild mate has an item that does illusion wearwolf.  Lately he gets asked for clarity a lot also.  How many of us have seen enchanters running around as wearwolfs, NOT in a newbie zone for the fright purposes?  That is a buff you cast on tanks or melee types, not on yourself!  /boggle<br>
<br>
Ah well, time to get off my soap box.  I just really am starting to hate people who beg and my message to them is normally, and I think from now on will be, &quot;I worked for what I have, please try to do the same and stop shaming the world of EQ with your pitifull begging&quot;.<br>
<br>
